# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1794-united-states-elections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first federal elections were held in the United States following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the elections, George Washington was elected as the first president and the members of the 1st United States Congress were selected.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Opposing them was the Anti-Administration faction, which sought a smaller role for the federal government.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In these elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Meanwhile, General George Washington was elected as the country's first president, while John Adams, who finished with the second largest number of electoral votes, was elected as the first vice president.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The presidential election of 1788–1789 was the first election of a federal head of state or head of government in United States history.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Congress of the Confederation had elected a president, but this position was one of legislative presiding officer and was not equivalent to the presidency that was established by the United States Constitution.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Constitution, the president was chosen by the Electoral College, which consisted of electors selected by each state.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, each elector cast two votes; the individual who received the most electoral votes would become president, while the individual who received the second-most electoral votes would become vice president.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] If no individual received votes from a majority of the electors, or if two individuals tied for the most votes, then the House of Representatives would select the president in a contingent election.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Under the Constitution, each state determines its own method of choosing presidential electors; in the 1788–1789 presidential election, many electors were appointed by state legislators, while others were chosen through elections.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the states that did hold elections, suffrage was generally restricted to white men who owned property.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] No party made a nomination for the presidency in the 1788–1789 presidential election, but several individuals vied for electoral votes.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] After his service in the American Revolutionary War, General George Washington was the first choice of many for president, but Washington was somewhat reluctant to re-enter public service.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The American public at large, however, wanted Washington to be the nation's first president.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first U.S. presidential campaign was, to some degree, what today would be called a grassroots effort to convince Washington to accept the office.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Alexander Hamilton was one of the most dedicated in his efforts to get Washington to accept the presidency, as he foresaw himself receiving a powerful position in the administration.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Less certain was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained little definitive job description in the constitution.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The only official role of the vice president was as the President of the United States Senate, a duty unrelated to the executive branch.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Because Washington was from Virginia, Washington (who remained neutral on the candidates) assumed that a vice president would be chosen from Massachusetts to provide sectional balance between the Northern states and the Southern states.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In an August 1788 letter, Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams, John Hancock, John Jay, James Madison, and John Rutledge to be contenders for the vice presidency.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Fearing an electoral college tie that could end with Adams winning the presidency, Alexander Hamilton arranged for several electors to vote for other candidates, including John Jay, who finished with the third most electoral votes.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] On April 6, 1789, the House and Senate, meeting in joint session, counted the electoral votes and certified that Washington had received electoral votes from each of the 69 electors that had cast votes, and thus had been elected president.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] They also certified that Adams, with 34 electoral votes, had been elected as vice president.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The other 35 electoral votes were divided among: John Jay (9), Robert H.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Harrison (6), John Rutledge (6), John Hancock (4), George Clinton (3), Samuel Huntington (2), John Milton (2), James Armstrong (1), Benjamin Lincoln (1), and Edward Telfair (1).
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Only ten of the thirteen states cast electoral votes; North Carolina and Rhode Island did not participate as they had not yet ratified the Constitution, while the New York legislature failed to appoint its allotted electors in time.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In 1788 and 1789, there were no political parties, but the major political split was between federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and anti-federalists who favored either completely rejecting the Constitution or only ratifying the document after making major changes to it.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] For example, in the election to represent Virginia's 5th congressional district, James Madison, a federalist who had played a major role in designing and ratifying the Constitution, defeated James Monroe, an anti-federalist who favored major changes to the Constitution.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In many elections, local issues and the personal popularity of the candidates played a more important role than positions on the Constitution and other national issues.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Retrospectively, political scientists and historians have divided the 1st Congress into members of the Pro-Administration and Anti-Administration factions.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction would generally support the centralizing economic policies of the Washington administration and Secretary of State Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction generally opposed those policies, instead favoring states' rights and a weaker federal government.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction overlapped heavily with both the federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and the later Federalist Party, while the Anti-Administration faction overlapped with the anti-federalists and the later Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Using this divide as a lens through which to view the elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Factional alignment would be fluid for much of the Washington administration.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] The first midterm elections were held in the United States in 1790 and 1791.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] They occurred in the middle of President George Washington's first term, and determined the members of the 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Formal political parties did not exist, but Congress was broadly divided between a faction supporting the policies of the Washington administration and a faction opposed to those policies.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Despite modest gains for the anti-administration faction, the pro-administration faction retained control of both houses of Congress.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Vermont and Kentucky joined the union during the 2nd Congress.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the House, neither faction made significant gains or losses, and the pro-administration faction retained control of the chamber.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the anti-administration faction picked up a moderate number of seats, but the pro-administration faction narrowly retained control of the chamber.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Elections were held for the 3rd United States Congress, in 1792 and 1793.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Congress was broadly divided between a Pro-Administration faction supporting the policies of George Washington's administration and an Anti-Administration faction opposed to those policies.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Due to this, the Federalist Party (generally overlapping with the Pro-Administration faction) and the Democratic-Republican Party (generally overlapping with the Anti-Administration faction) were starting to emerge as the distinct political parties of the First Party System.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In this election, the Pro-Administration faction maintained control of the Senate, but lost its majority in the House.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the presidential election, incumbent President George Washington was re-elected without any major opposition.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington had considered retirement, but was convinced to seek re-election for the purpose of national unity.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Though Washington went unchallenged, Governor George Clinton of New York sought to unseat John Adams as vice president.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Adams received the second most electoral votes, and so was re-elected to office.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington remained unaffiliated with any political faction or party throughout his presidency.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the House, 37 seats were added following the 1790 census.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction picked up several seats, narrowly taking the majority from the Pro-Administration faction.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Frederick Muhlenberg, who leaned closer to the Pro-Administration faction, was elected Speaker of the House.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the Anti-Administration faction picked up one seat, but the Pro-Administration faction maintained a small majority.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1794–95 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 25, 1794 (New Hampshire), and September 5, 1795 (Kentucky).
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 4th United States Congress convened on December 7, 1795.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They were held during President George Washington's second term.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections were held for all 105 seats, representing 15 states.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the first election for the House of Representatives with organized political parties, the Democratic-Republican Party, which opposed the incumbent Washington Administration, defeated the pro-administration Federalist Party.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The outgoing speaker, Frederick Muhlenberg, had supported the pro-administration forces during his first two terms, but was elected by a coalition made up mainly of anti-administration members in 1793, and by 1795 he was seen as more favorable to the Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Despite the Democratic-Republican majority, however, Muhlenberg was not re-elected, and was succeeded by Federalist Jonathan Dayton.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] During this period, each state fixed its own date for a congressional general election.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when a Congress convened.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 3rd and 4th Congresses in 1794 and 1795.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only two candidates are recorded for Delaware's congressional election in 1794, suggesting that the voting procedure in place for the first three Congresses for two candidates had been changed.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts redistricted between the 3rd and 4th Congress, dividing itself into 14 districts.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 12th-14th districts were in the District of Maine (the modern State of Maine).
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Additional ballots were required in five districts due to the majority requirement not being met on the first ballot.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under New Hampshire's electoral laws, a majority of voters (12.5% of votes) was required for election.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only three candidates achieved a majority, and so a run-off election was held for the fourth seat.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, but were later numbered retroactively.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania once again divided itself into districts instead of electing representatives at-large, as it had for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The state divided intself into 12 districts, one of which (the 4th) had two seats.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania would continue to use one or more plural districts until 1842.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Electoral data are only available for the 1st and 5th district of South Carolina's 6 districts at the time of the elections of 1794.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representative-elect Barnwell of the 2nd district declined to serve.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A special election was held to fill the resulting vacancy, electing Wade Hampton (Democratic-Republican).
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law required a majority for election to Congress, with a second election to be held if the first did not return a majority.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Run-off elections were required in both districts.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] The **1794–95 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1794 and 1795, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 3.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] This was the first election cycle with organized political parties in the United States, with the Federalist Party emerging from the Pro Administration coalition, and the Democratic-Republican Party emerging from the Anti-Administration coalition.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] After the March 31, 1794 special election in Pennsylvania.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Seven senators who were considered "Anti-Administration" became Democratic-Republicans and eleven "Pro-Administration" became Federalists.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Except if/when noted, the number following candidates is the whole number vote(s), not a percentage.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] In these special elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1795; ordered by election date.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1795; ordered by state.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] All of the elections involved the Class 3 seats.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] There were no elections in 1795 after March 4.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] The **Delaware special election** was held February 7, 1795.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent Senator George Read had resigned to take the position of Chief Justice of the Delaware Supreme Court.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Henry Latimer defeated the former Governor of Delaware, Governor of Pennsylvania and Continental Congressmen from Delaware and Pennsylvania by one vote.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] John Henry won election over James Lloyd by an unknown number of votes for the Class 3 seat.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent Federalist Robert Morris, who was elected in 1788, was not a candidate for re-election to another term.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] The Pennsylvania General Assembly convened on February 26, 1795, to elect a senator for the term beginning March 4, 1795.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Even though neither of Virginia's incumbent's terms were up, both resigned in 1794, leading to two special elections.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Future-president James Monroe resigned March 27, 1794 to become U.S.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Stevens Thomson Mason was elected November 18, 1794 and would become a Democratic-Republican in the next Congress.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent John Taylor of Caroline resigned May 11, 1794.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-95-united-states-senate-elections] Henry Tazewell was elected November 18, 1794 and would become a Democratic-Republican in the next Congress.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Elections occurred in the middle of President George Washington's second term.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Members of the 4th United States Congress were chosen in this election.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Tennessee was admitted as a state during the 4th Congress.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] The election took place at the beginning of the First Party System, with the Democratic-Republican Party and Federalist Party emerging as political parties, succeeding the anti-administration faction and the pro-administration faction.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] In the House, the Democratic-Republicans picked up a small number of seats, increasing their majority.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] However, Federalist Jonathan Dayton was elected Speaker of the House, defeating Frederick Muhlenberg, who had a less clear partisan affiliation.
[src:1794-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the Federalists picked up a moderate number of seats, increasing their majority.
